folder: Bleecker Street & 7th Avenue South, Manhattan, NY
text:
Bleecker Street, northeast side, north from Seventh Avenue South, across Grove, to Christopher Street's. The two blocks shown are the last of the section that passed thru the former Herring Farm, and was called Herring Street. The triangular block in the foreground exists since the cutting thru of Seventh Avenue in 1915. Antiquated attic structures seen are No's. 305-7 & 309. The latter, formerly No. 293, is the house in which Thomas Paine lived from July, 1808, to April, 1809. At this time Herring Street was newly opened. View No. 2 is of the Doll's House Tea Room located in the tin shack at the apex. Anna Mescia of Grantwood is the property owner and will commission S. Schuman, architect, to design a two story dwelling and store for this site. This is to cost $12,000 as reported in the New York Times of April 27, 1939.

No. 1: 1922
2: Sept. 26, 1928

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

P. L. Sperr

folder: Bleecker Street & 7th Avenue South, Manhattan, NY
text:
Bleecker Street, northeast side, north from Seventh Avenue South. The aged buildings appearing in the foreground are No's. 305-7 (a double house) and 309. The latter is the Thomas Paine home of 1808-9. At that date this thoroughfare was known as Herring Street and had just been opened. View No. 2 is slightly earlier and shows the tin garage (No. 303) used as a tea room. No. 3 is still earlier and is in the opposite direction being photographed from a point above Grove Street.

folder: Commerce Street & 7th Avenue, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Commerce Street, south side, west from Seventh Ave., and across Bedford Street. This street at the far end makes a right angle bend northward, to terminate at Barrow Street. The 2½-story structures with the dormer windows are frame buildings and are separated by a 4-story tenement, that was formerly a factory.

May 19, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, in the opposite direction (eastward) as seen from a point west of Bedford Street and showing a 2½-story frame house at the S.W. corner of Bedford and Commerce Streets. This building bears No. 77 Bedford Street.

May 27, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

text:
Seventh Avenue South, adjoining and at the S.E. corner of Bleecker Street, the former S.W. corner of Bleecker and Commerce Streets, showing the rear of 286 and 284 (old Nos. 270 and 268) Bleecker Street, the former slightly truncated by the avenue. folder: 7th Avenue & Barrow Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Seventh Avenue, (left) at the N. E. corner of Barrow Street (right) showing a gas station which formerly occupied property belonging to two separate owners. Because of difficulties the tenant was dispossessed from the corner plot and the owner had same fenced in. A story giving details was recently carried in either the New York Sun or Times.

VIEW 2 is another angle of same scene.

September 16, 1938
Views 1 and 2

George D. Chinn
